But instead all I got was “I don’t know what to do with her, give her a diagnosis and fix her” “she can’t be fixed.”

If just one person had told me I wasn’t broken things would’ve been different.

It would’ve been helpful to hear “ADHD describes how your brain processes things. It’s why you’re good at tests, writing, math, art, etc. It’s why you can’t get going until the last minute. It’s why you only feel awake when you’re excited. It’s why you have strong emotions.” etc.

That wasn’t super helpful. Everyone was just telling me all the things they’ve been yelling at me about are caused by this incurable thing I can’t do anything about. Then no one listened to me about my meds making me depressed because they’re a “stimulant”.

If someone had taken the time to give me the information I have now, I don’t think my productivity would’ve differed but my mental health might’ve.

I thought everyone was trying to put me in this “inevitable failure box”.

“Your ADHD is what makes you lazy, annoying, and late.”

I remember asking how it can be cured. My psychiatrist said it can’t be. That derailed about 5 years of my life.

“Can’t” and “Doesn’t need to be” Are very different and she chose “can’t”.
It’s important to keep in mind that kids don’t have as much exposure or nuance with terms. When they find out they have ADHD they probably think it’s a mental illness.

A Kid’s Experience with the Term, “ADHD”

And even though I was 8 I was like yeah dude that’s what I’ve been trying to tell y’all about me! Let me do my own thing and I can be like him. Obviously it was a long way from me being able to create my own goals and my own map to them. But I’m grateful I have that freedom now.

He had giant out of this world ideas that no one understood until he finished. I remember one quote was something like, “the simplest deep thinker I know.” Always thinking about the small pieces creating a big picture.

He’d do terribly in school because he would never answer the questions directly. He always needed more details, more connections. He’d think of something great at the last second and miss deadlines from “obsessively” working on every part being connected.+

They would say he was smart but very lazy. It was a miracle he got anything done because he was so chaotic and messy. He was so unorganized but he preferred his office stay that way. He often jumped from one thing to another to spark creativity on the first thing. +

I always saw myself in Einstein when we’d talk about him in school. Not because I considered myself a genius or even because I cared about science. It just felt like they were describing me when teachers spoke about him.

Leonardo Da Vinci was often criticized for not being able to stick to one thing consistently. They were mad when he wasn’t doing whatever thing they deemed him best at. He simply continued doing what was best for him.

When you’re looking around at all these people who started at level 1 on a skill and stayed consistent with it to level 50, it can be discouraging to be like the previous example. But what we don’t think of is that we have developed many skills on many different levels.

We might get really into photography, learn all the different tech that comes with photo editing and create a small portfolio. We think “wow I’ve found what I want to do!” Then we get bored and find ourselves doing the same thing with woodworking a month later.
However, because our brains are constantly going and constantly asking questions, difficult subjects engage us. Specific and challenging goals are our road maps to building skills.

While ADHDers may struggle with the basics, we’re actually great with complexities. The reason for having a hard time with first level subjects is that they aren’t engaging and the information doesn’t stick. Most require memorization; not our strong suit.
It turns out, no. Apparently Leonardo Da Vinci, myself, and many others all have something in common: ADHD.

She did not disappoint. I cried as soon as I picked up the package even though I knew what it was. My mom cried when I gave her hers. My dad hugged his. These mean so much to us and I’m so thankful to @LindseyDoesThis for giving us a happy reminder of our boy on Christmas 🥰 https://t.co/qY8Yxr8PNE

I sent some pictures of Danny and asked if somehow his favorite toy (his tire) and his favorite spot (our bay window) could be included.

I wanted Lindsey to do this because her style is so joyful and colorful. I needed a reminder that would make me think of Danny not his death. https://t.co/9b2a99sYCI

So, for our first Christmas without him, I wanted something to remember Danny. But photos just remind me he’s in the past. I wanted something new with Danny in it, even though that’s not possible.

Then @artoflindseyjnx posted about commissioned pet ornaments.

Danny was the bright spot in our family. And even though my parents divorced at the beginning of the pandemic, we’re still a family. We’ve all just been carrying this really heavy and unexpected loss. With the pandemic, we’ve also all been separated and carrying the loss alone.

That’s why, when we found out he had cancer, we didn’t even question the biweekly 2 hour drive to the closest clinic familiar with this rare cancer.

They estimated, after treatments, he had about 6 more months and they were right. He passed away last year.

Caffeine in tea binds with L-theanine. It releases bit by bit. It assists with focus.
